<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<assessmentItem xmlns="http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/imsqti_v2p1"
                xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
                xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/imsqti_v2p1 http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/imsqti_v2p1.xsd"
                identifier="WhatIsAnEquation" title="What Is An Equation" adaptive="false"
                timeDependent="false">
    <responseDeclaration identifier="RESPONSE" cardinality="multiple" baseType="identifier">
        <correctResponse>
            <value>ChoiceA</value>
            <value>ChoiceD</value>
            <value>ChoiceE</value>
        </correctResponse>
        <mapping lowerBound="0" upperBound="3">
            <mapEntry mapKey="ChoiceA" mappedValue="1"/>
            <mapEntry mapKey="ChoiceD" mappedValue="1"/>
            <mapEntry mapKey="ChoiceE" mappedValue="1"/>
        </mapping>
    </responseDeclaration>
    <outcomeDeclaration identifier="SCORE" cardinality="single" baseType="float"/>
    <itemBody>
        <p>
            Let us recall the match stick pattern of forming triangle. For our convenience, figure is redrawn below
        </p>
        <p>
            <p>1)</p>
            <img src="images/matchstick-triangle-1.png" height="100px" width="120px" alt="Match Stick Triangle 1"/>
        </p>
        <p>
            <p>2)</p>
            <img src="images/matchstick-triangle-2.png" height="100px" width="240px" alt="Match Stick Triangle 2"/>
        </p>
        <p>
            <p>3)</p>
            <img src="images/matchstick-triangle-3.png" height="100px" width="360px" alt="Match Stick Triangle 3"/>
        </p>
        <p>
            Table below shows the number of match sticks required for different number of triangles formed.
        </p>
        <table class="table table-bordered">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Number of triangles</th>
                    <th>1</th>
                    <th>2</th>
                    <th>3</th>
                    <th>4</th>
                    <th>5</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>Number of match sticks used</td>
                    <td>
                        3
                    </td>
                    <td>
                        6
                    </td>
                    <td>
                        9
                    </td>
                    <td>
                        12
                    </td>
                    <td>
                        15
                    </td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
            We know that the number of match sticks required is given by the rule
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            ,
            where
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            is number of triangles formed.
            <br/>
            <br/>
            Lets think differently,
            <em>We know how to find the number of match sticks required for given number of
                triangles.
                What about the other way round? How does one find the number of triangles formed, given the number of
                match
                sticks
            </em>
            ?
        </p>
        <p>
            Lets ask ourselves a definite question. How many triangles are formed if the number of match sticks given is
            12?
            This means we have to find the number of triangles, given the number of match sticks is 12. So,
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>12</m:mn>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
        </p>
        <p>
            Here, <strong>we have a condition to be satisfied by the variable </strong>
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            . This condition is an example of an<code>equation</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Our question can be answered by looking at below table. Look at the various values of
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            . if
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            ,
            the number of match sticks is 3. Clearly, the condition is not satisfied, because 3 is no 12.
            We go on checking
            <table class="table table-bordered">
                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <th>
                            <m:math>
                                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                </m:mstyle>
                            </m:math>
                        </th>
                        <th>
                            <m:math>
                                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                                    <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                </m:mstyle>
                            </m:math>
                        </th>
                        <th>Condition satisfied.? Yes/No</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            1
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            3
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            No
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            2
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            6
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            No
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            3
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            9
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            No
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            4
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            12
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            Yes
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            5
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            15
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            No
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </p>
        <p>
            We find that only if
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            ,
            the condition i.e the equation
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>12</m:mn>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            is satisfied. For any value of
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            other than 4, the equation is not satisfied.
        </p>
        <p>
            To summarise,
            <strong>
                Any equation like the above, is a condition on a variable. It is satisfied only for a definite value of
                the variable.
            </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            Note that an equation has an
            <strong>equal sign (=)</strong>
            between its two sides. if left hand side (LHS) is not equal to
            the right hand side (RHS) we do not get the equation.
            <br/>
            For example : The statement
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                    <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            is greater than 10, i.e
            <m:math title="2n > 10" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                    <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                    <m:mo>&gt;</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>10</m:mn>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            is not an equation.
            Also the statements
            <m:math title="(x-3)>11" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mrow>
                        <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>-</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                        <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                    </m:mrow>
                    <m:mo>&gt;</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>11</m:mn>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            or
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle mathcolor="blue" fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mrow>
                        <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>-</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                        <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                    </m:mrow>
                    <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>11</m:mn>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            are not equations.
        </p>
        <p>
            Now, let us consider 8 - 3 = 5
            There is an equal sign between LHS and RHS. Neither of the two sides contain a variable. We may call this a
            <code>numerical equation</code>.
            The word equation is used only for the equations with one or more variables.
        </p>
        <p><strong>Check your understanding</strong></p>
        <div class="well">
            <choiceInteraction responseIdentifier="RESPONSE" maxChoices="0">
                <prompt>
                    <h4>Identify which of the following are equations.</h4>
                    <br/>
                </prompt>
                <simpleChoice identifier="ChoiceA">
                    <m:math title="x+20=70">
                        <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                            <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>20</m:mn>
                            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>70</m:mn>
                        </m:mstyle>
                    </m:math>
                </simpleChoice>
                <simpleChoice identifier="ChoiceB">8 x 3 = 24</simpleChoice>
                <simpleChoice identifier="ChoiceC">
                    <m:math>
                        <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                            <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                            <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>&gt;</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>30</m:mn>
                        </m:mstyle>
                    </m:math>
                </simpleChoice>
                <simpleChoice identifier="ChoiceD">
                    <m:math>
                        <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                            <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>-</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>100</m:mn>
                        </m:mstyle>
                    </m:math>
                </simpleChoice>
                <simpleChoice identifier="ChoiceE">
                    <m:math>
                        <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                            <m:mn>20</m:mn>
                            <m:mi>b</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>80</m:mn>
                        </m:mstyle>
                    </m:math>
                </simpleChoice>
                <simpleChoice identifier="ChoiceF">
                    <m:math>
                        <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                            <m:mfrac>
                                <m:mi>y</m:mi>
                                <m:mn>8</m:mn>
                            </m:mfrac>
                            <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>50</m:mn>
                        </m:mstyle>
                    </m:math>
                </simpleChoice>
            </choiceInteraction>
        </div>
    </itemBody>
    <responseProcessing
            template="http://www.imsglobal.org/question/qti_v2p1/rptemplates/map_response"/>
</assessmentItem>
